hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Low-temperature heat capacity per unit area:
$$C=\frac{\pi^2}{3}\,g(E_F)\,k_B^2 T.$$
Thus
$$\frac{C_B}{C_A}=\frac{g_B(E_{F,B})}{g_A(E_{F,A})}.$$

2. System A (parabolic dispersion):
$$E_A(k)=\frac{\hbar^2 k^2}{2m},\quad n=\frac{k_{F,A}^2}{2\pi}\;\Rightarrow\;k_{F,A}=\sqrt{2\pi n},$$
$$g_A(E)=\frac{m}{\pi\hbar^2},\quad g_A(E_{F,A})=\frac{m}{\pi\hbar^2}.$$

3. System B (linear dispersion):
$$E_B(k)=\hbar v_F k,\quad n=\frac{k_{F,B}^2}{2\pi}\;\Rightarrow\;k_{F,B}=\sqrt{2\pi n},$$
$$N(E)=\frac{2\pi k^2}{(2\pi)^2}=\frac{k^2}{2\pi},\quad g_B(E)=\frac{dN}{dE}
=\frac{dN}{dk}\frac{dk}{dE}
=\frac{2k}{2\pi}\frac{1}{\hbar v_F}
=\frac{k}{\pi\hbar v_F}.$$
At the Fermi level,
$$g_B(E_{F,B})=\frac{k_{F,B}}{\pi\hbar v_F}
=\frac{\sqrt{2\pi n}}{\pi\hbar v_F}.$$

4. Use the condition $v_F=v_{F,A}=\hbar k_{F,A}/m=\hbar\sqrt{2\pi n}/m$:
$$g_B(E_{F,B})
=\frac{\sqrt{2\pi n}}{\pi\hbar(\hbar\sqrt{2\pi n}/m)}
=\frac{m}{\pi\hbar^2}
=g_A(E_{F,A}).$$

5. Therefore,
$$\frac{C_B}{C_A}
=\frac{g_B(E_{F,B})}{g_A(E_{F,A})}
=1.$$
